TextEquiv.Unicode: For let us suppose a human legislator
to conduct himself upon the same principles
as our Author attributes to the Creator to act.
Let us suppose him to have published a law
which was to serve as the rule of conduct to his
people: let us suppose, that the principal
person among his People had violated this
law: that he had afterwards secreted it from
the rest, and put it absolutely out of their power
to come at the knowledge of it: This is surely the
very case which our Author supposes to have
happened to mankind in general: The legisla=­
­tor still insists upon obedience to the same
